Brazilian Stock Movers: B2W, Pao de Acucar, Tele Norte, Tim, Tam

-- B y   L e o n   L a z a r o f f
-- 
2011-03-28T21:30:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-28/brazilian-stock-movers-vale-pao-de-acucar-tim-redecard.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in Sao Paulo trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4 p.m. New York time. Preferred
shares are usually the most-traded class of stock.  The Bovespa Index fell 0.9 percent to 67,192.82.  Tele Norte Leste Participacoes SA (TNLP3)  (TNLP3 BS),  Brazil ’s
biggest fixed-line phone company known as Oi, rose 5.4 percent
to 37.75 reais. Chief Executive Officer Luiz Eduardo Falco Pires
Correa said he has a contract with the company until the end of
the year and will fulfill the commitment. Falco was speaking at
an event in  Rio de Janeiro .  B2W Cia. Global do Varejo (BTOW3 BS), Brazil’s largest
online retailer, fell 3.6 percent to 21.92 reais. Economists
covering the Brazilian economy raised their 2011 inflation
forecast, saying they project a 6 percent increase in consumer
prices instead of the 5.88 percent jump they had projected last
week, according to the median estimate in a March 25 weekly
central bank survey of about 100 economists published today. The
2012 inflation forecast was increased to 4.91 percent from 4.8
percent.  Tim Participacoes SA (TCSL4)  (TCSL4 BS), the voting shares of
Brazilian unit of  Italy ’s largest phone company, rose 0.9
percent to 7.12 reais, as the telecommunications regulator
Anatel said Brazil’s mobile-home market expanded 1.18 percent in
February. Tim rose for the seventh consecutive trading day.  Tam SA (TAMM4)  (TAMM4 BS), Brazil’s biggest airline by market share
fell 2 percent to 31.84 reais. Banco Santander SA said in an
investor report today that jet fuel costs have the potential to
“significantly impact” the profitability of Latin American
airlines. It cited Tam and Gol as airlines where profitability
may be sensitive to fuel variations.  Cia. Brasileira de Distribuicao Grupo Pao de Acucar (PCAR5
BS), Brazil’s largest retailer, dropped 0.7 percent to 64.11
reais. Antitrust regulators said the company will have to sell
stores to win approval for the purchase of Globex Utilidades SA
and Casas Bahia Comercial Ltda.  Vale SA (VALE3)  (VALE5 BS), the world’s biggest iron-ore producer,
fell 0.9 percent to 46.47 reais as copper for May delivery fell
6.9 cents, or 1.6 percent, to $4.35 a pound at 1:12 p.m. on the
Comex in New York. Controlling shareholders may oust Chief
Executive Officer Roger Agnelli in favor of another executive
within the company, said a person close to one of the investors
on March 25. The person declined to be named because talks
aren’t public.  Usinas Siderurgicas de Minas Gerais SA (USIM5)  (USIM5 BS) declined
2 percent to 19.08 reais as Brazil’s second-largest steelmaker
said its pension fund announced that it doesn’t have a contract
to sell a stake in the company. Usiminas, as the steelmaker is
known, made the comments in a regulatory filing today in
response to news reports that the fund had hired some banks to
sell the shares. Usiminas fell for the sixth consecutive trading
day.  To contact the reporter on this story:
